blicProfile>TheRedhand</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/image/globalBlack.gif BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Global user</span><br>   <font color=#939393>(3/24/00 12:07:38 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Morrigu's early years</span><hr size=1> Morrigu was born into the prominent F'Lok family, the daughter of powerful Wizards. A bright young child with green eyes like her mother, Tasriel, she was naturally adept at the magical arts. Her mother was the creator of the famed &quot;Ice Comet&quot; spell, and was killed in an assault on Kelethin in one of the first practical uses of this spell. Lady F'Lok took many Feir'Dal and Koada'Dal to their deaths before being slain by a Feir'Dal druid named Gaiean. Upon news of the failed assault reaching Neriak, Morrigu's father, the Lord Razran F'Lok, went into a catatonia of sorts. He can still be seen on the tower of the Wizard's guild, silent and randomly casting a spell here or there. Effectively orphaned at her tender age, her brother Antian took over her care in the hours he was not at his bank, counting his all-important money. Feeling abandoned by all around her, Morrigu forswore her education in the mystic arts. Leaving both the Wizards academy and her brother's care, and despising his company and ethics, Morrigu set out to become the most skilled slayer of men that she could. She vowed to one day put a knife in the back of the druid Gaeian and ALL his kind. During her studies of anatomy and testing her powers at striking living creatures, her eyes shifted their color from green to blood red (seemingly the hate inside of her has made other physiological changes, but she rarely holds still for examination or documentation of these changes). Morrigu lives to see the day that all other breeds of elves are yoked in slavery under the Teir'Dal and other Dark Races.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#242422><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/utheredhand.showPublicProfile>TheRedhand</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/image/globalBlack.gif BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Global user</span><br>   <font color=#939393>(3/24/00 12:11:46 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> A home at last!</span><hr size=1> At long last, after leaving my Mad father and money-hungry brother, I have found a home for my restless spirit. These folk seem to despise the light-dwellers as much as I. I have found a surrogate Mother in the House Matron Quelui S'Renn, a sister of my heart in my House Leader Lady Kierra e'Kieron, and a brother of spirit and blood in Lord Kiros e'Kieron. Daymar D'Vraek, Jahet, Illan Do'Djen, Ralex and a very amusing Troll named Quash Frogbiter round outthis motley band of brethren who have welcomed me with open arms...<br>
<br>
Ulu z'hin maglust dal Qu'ellar lueth Ilharess zhah ulu z'hin wund lil phalar! <br>
(To walk apart from Hose and Matron is to walk into the grave)  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/utheredhand.showPublicProfile>TheRedhand</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/image/globalBlack.gif BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Global user</span><br>   <font color=#939393>(3/24/00 12:13:28 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> I return to find all in chaos</span><hr size=1> After a long absence away from our sacred home, I return to find that my Brother Kiros has been slain, many new cousins in the house, and my beloved Kaelin as absent from the land as I have been. This merits a closer eye on the goings-on, and as Leader of the Sisters of Iosse (who as of yet have no members...) I will need to play my part, instead of selfishly attending to my personal whims.... <br>
<br>
Lil alurl velve zhah lil velkyn uss <br>
The best knife is the unseen one  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#242422><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/utheredhand.showPublicProfile>TheRedhand</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/image/globalBlack.gif BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Global user</span><br>   <font color=#939393>(3/24/00 12:15:37 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> A debacle of bloodletting in the deserts of Ro</span><hr size=1> Morrigu had received the call from a messanger of the house D'Fral. She reluctantly put down her pitcher of Kalish, then picked it backup and drained it before moving away from her table and out the door. She headed directly for the Oasis of Marr, where the EVENT was to take place. Upon her arrival in the oasis, she saw that the EVENT had already begun. Achren was speaking civilly and attempting to initiate a debate as to why the lightskins and the Dark Races warred constantly, but the speech was so thick it was a babble. She was jeered and insulted at every sentance. Morrigu polished her blades conspicuously, indicating a willingness to shut the mouths of those who were NOT her for debate. <br>
<br>
Shortly, Morrigu's old friend Xandriel arrived and made her presence known to Morrigu with a playful poke in the ribs. Xandriel was hidden and for a moment, even Morrigu's skills could not locate her, in the hot sun of the northern desert of Ro. Xan was becoming skilled indeed. Morrigu felt a swell of sisterly pride in her former guildmate. She clasped Xandriel's hand and savored the moment, knowing it might not come again soon. Passing a few bottles of Gypsy wine to Xandriel for refreshment, Morrigu's heart rejoiced for the first time in a long while. <br>
<br>
Very rapidly the challenges flew, and the Brother of her Blood, Kiros E'Kieron, accepted a duel from the Valorblade Rogue, Vankane. Vankane was a fellow rogue, and quick as any of his kind. Kiros was at a disadvantage for having chosen the Halberd as his weapon, but Kiros knew his own methods best. Vankane started off with a backstab and a flurry of short stabs, true to form for their profession. No assassin, like herself, but a worthy thief in his own right. Kiros recovered, and responded with heavy blows from his halberd. Then we all noticed a song filtering through the air, a soft, gentle melody accompanied by a blue aura that linked Vankane to a young bard from his guild. “Foul!” the Teir'Dal cried, only to be jeered by the lightskins. Kiros was eventually struck down by Vankane, with the assistance of the healing song from his bard. <br>
<br>
The talks degenerated more (truth to tell Morrigu was singlemindedly pursuing a duel with the reluctant bard to avenger her Brother's defeat) and eventually Achren and Mystere, both disgusted, left. <br>
<br>
Few indeed were left to represent the Teir'Dal. Before the eyes of her cousin Tholith the Necromancer, Furios the Human challenged Morrigu to duel, and she accepted upon his word that there would be no interferance. True to their word, Valorblade kept it clean, and the spectators did, too. The fight was largely one-sided, and at one point Morrigu stopped and asked Furios if he yielded to her. Morrigu enjoys little more than the shedding of blood, but there was a higher purpose here today. A proud member of the Knights of Valorblade, Furios declined the offer to cease and battled on. Morrigu bowed to him and dispatched him quickly. Then the Woodsie Rupert, the one with a loud mouth, challenged Morrigu instantly upon her victory. This battle was not so one-sided, and Rupert laned a few nice blows. Again, she asked her opponent if he yielded to her, and to his credit he did not. &quot;Never!&quot; he cried, and threw himself into the fray with a will. Morrigu concentrated on her actions and after a flurry of short blows, dispatched him also. She received a few more challenges, but made it clear her business was with Korie the wood elf bard who had interfered in Kiros' duel. <br>
<br>
Korie stepped up and with honor challenged Morrigu to fight. Morrigu was half-dead at this point and the question was raised among the mixed crowd whether she should be healed first, but the Assasin waved them off. If this young bard had honor and dignity enough to challenge her better to reclaim her good name, Morrigu would fight as she was, and let the Gods and her skill decide. Korie fought with skill and determination, landing several good strikes, and singing her songs at every opportunity. The Teir'Dal in the crowd cried &quot;Foul!&quot; again, but Morrigu announced that Korie was free to use all her skills to fight for her own honor. Towards the end of the battle, it was clear that Korie was going to die, and Morrigu backed away and gave her the chance to yield. A Knight of Valorblade ever, Korie chose the honorable way to repay her debt and did not yield. Morrigu battled her into unconciousness, and while the child slumbered, softly dispatched her with a blow to the spine. A fine opponent, and a woman of Honor and Dignity, Korie was. <br>
<br>
Morrigu stepped away from the battle, weary and grievously wounded, and sat down heavily. &quot;No More!&quot; she cried, &quot;I will slay no more of your clan tonight! Valorblade has proven themselves honorable indeed!&quot; A high elf woman stepped up to bandage Morrigu's wounds while a wood elf cast healing spells upon her. She had earned a modicum of respect for her race. Morrigu felt as if her chest would swell till it exploded… Innoruuk had smiled upon her, indeed. <br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/utheredhand.showPublicProfile>TheRedhand</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/image/globalBlack.gif BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Global user</span><br>   <font color=#939393>(3/24/00 12:16:27 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> The house of D'Fral grows complacent</span><hr size=1> Morrigu sat and sipped her wine, not carousing in her hideout in the Foriegn Quarter for once, but quiet in her home in the Third Gate of Neriak. As a member of the prominent F'Lok family, she claimed a place in the richly coveted Third Gate by right of pure blood. <br>
The Obsidian Blade was becoming complacent, and her Blood-brother Kiros E'Kieron had begun to be frustrated with their lack of forward motion. Morrigu would have to speak with the Matron on this matter... <br>
Morrigu HATED politics, but she was born into them. She had to admit, she did love the outcome of political intrigue, which was usually either hired assasinations or war. Either way, Morrigu profitted in wealth or the sheer joy of bloodletting. Still... how long could a war against such clans as Valorblade last? Most light-skinned guilds recruited without much care for thequality of their members, and swelled their ranks with children who spoke in a near-incomprehensible jargon. And the light-skins themselves bred so quickly as to nearly crowd the rest of the world out by sheer force of numbers. Ah, the Teir'Dal were used to fighting as underdogs, though. <br>
Yet lately, Morrigu had witnessed a strange occurence in the Forest outside of Neriak. Young Teir'Dal with names that were clearly foreign, half-breeds who were in spirit and action more like unto the lightskins than their own blood-kin! <br>
Morrigu shook her head slowly and drew a heavy breath. This would be a long battle, indeed.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#242422><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/utheredhand.showPublicProfile>TheRedhand</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/image/globalBlack.gif BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Global user</span><br>   <font color=#939393>(3/24/00 12:18:04 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> An early tale in the Faydark Forest</span><hr size=1> During one of her characteristic drunken wanderings, Morrigu happened upon a <br>
quiet patch of forest where a young <br>
Feir'Dal girl sat playing a battered lute. The wood-elf child looked up at <br>
Morrigu's quiet approach. &quot;Oh! Hello!&quot; She said, <br>
only slightly taken aback at the sight of a dark elf in these most sacred of <br>
woods. &quot;Would you like to do the Bards a favor <br>
and deliver some ma.....&quot; the words abruptly ceased as she looked closer at <br>
Morrigu. &quot;Umm...do I know you, friend? You <br>
seem familiar..perhaps we have met...?&quot; <br>
<br>
Morrigu chuckled quietly, knowing that her bounty had been posted in many <br>
cities on Faydwer for her &quot;atrocities&quot; to the Feir'Dal race. &quot;Those <br>
blood-red eyes...that scar upon your shoulder...you're the Redhand!!!&quot; the <br>
little Feir'Dal squeaked, and grabbing her pack, began running as fast as <br>
her songs could speed her along, shrieking for the guards. &quot;This won't do at <br>
all&quot; thought Morrigu, and slipped quietly into the trees, practicing her <br>
newly learned shadow-stepping skills. <br>
<br>
Soon the young wood-elf ran directly into a wall of blue corded muscle and <br>
cold hate. The forest was quickly silent of <br>
both song and shrieks. Digging through the girl's personal effects, Morrigu <br>
found a rolled parchment, which read so: <br>
<br>
&quot;A song composed for the event of my own death: <br>
<br>
'Under Veeshan's starry sky, <br>
dig the grave where I'll softly lie. <br>
For Tunare I lived, and gladly died, <br>
and played my songs for others. <br>
<br>
This be the verse you sing for me, <br>
'Here she lies, where she longed to be <br>
Home the singer, ever free, <br>
And the daughter home to the Mother' <br>
<br>
Calliope Winddancer&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;Hmmm...&quot; thought Morrigu, &quot;quite a nice tune there&quot;. She arranged the girls <br>
body in a face-down position on the forest <br>
floor, scattering bits of sweetmeats to attract the scavengers of the <br>
forest. There was no way she would waste the effort to <br>
dig this girl her grave...besides, the guards of the nearby city would <br>
surely get a delightful shock at seeing the girl's half-eaten body <br>
lying there. A pleasant thought indeed. She pulled off the glove from her <br>
right hand and stuffed it just inside the boot of the <br>
girl. The bit of crimson silk should stay put despite the best efforts of <br>
hungry wolves, and would serve as a nice reminder <br>
that Morrigu went wherever she damn well pleased. She picked up the girl's <br>
lute, and scarce valuables, and moved on, <br>
humming a strange haunting little tune to herself all the way back to the <br>
Dwarven mountains and the boat home. <br>
Morrigu the Redhand <br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/utheredhand.showPublicProfile>TheRedhand</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/image/globalBlack.gif BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Global user</span><br>   <font color=#939393>(3/24/00 12:19:05 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> The weight of Command</span><hr size=1> <br>
Morrigu paces the floor in the F'Lok house in the Third Gate area of Neriak. Her two older brothers, Antian and Drav, are both seeing to their assigned duties while performing their professional roles. Antian, being eldest, was at first reluctant to release the reigns of power for the house to Morrigu. After all, she WAS younger by several decades. A demonstration of her Will had been necessary to send him scuttling obediantly back to his vault to count the money he kept for others. It was not as if she were ungrateful for all those years he spent raising her, she just needed him to show some strength of purpose. Drav, owever, had political aspirations and was happy to see a strong woman at the head of the household again, it earned him respect in his job as a city guard, even if his sister was younger than he. <br>
<br>
Things had been strange for her since returning to the house she had grown up in. She had no time at all now, what with her house duties and political hobnobbing, to visit that noisy bar in the Foreign Quarter she had become so fond of. Of course her spies still maintained a drop-off there, and information was pouring in from all sides, with one conspicous gap in her information network. Hmm... <br>
<br>
She no longer took commisions for assassination, she now managed those requests as a collateral duty to her house. Teir'Dal she had been paid by before now work FOR her. It was a satisfying time, in theory. So why didn't she FEEL fulfilled? A faint twinge ran through her when she thought of her first days with House D'Fral, her TRUE family. A fine time, all bloodlust and killing and carousing. Things had gotten so...serious lately. She sighed as she shifted her weight again, spinning around to pace through another part of the almost-unfamiliar house. The mantle of authority weighed heavy on her, and she looked forward to the day she could turn it over to another. But not yet. Not until one more worthy came from within her own house. <br>
<br>
She signalled to a nearby houseslave, and ordered a tray of sweetmeats to be sent to her Father's feet in the Neriak Commons, atop the Wizard's tower. Razran was never seen to speak or eat, but food set before him would eventually disappear. She wondered if he would EVER come back to himself, or if he would be fully and truly mad till the end of his days, pining for Tasriel until he one day just faded from the world. <br>
<br>
Ahh, and the Wizards... they had been most keen to have her return to her studies with them now that she had taken control of her house. They spoke to her of their pride in her Mother's abilities, and how Morrigu so resembled the great Tasriel F'Lok. No doubt they merely wanted a Wizard of their guild, no matter her caliber, to hold some political standing in the community. No, she would not return to the studies of her early days. But she WAS picking a few things up, already a new, albeit weak, power came to her on occasion. She had discovered a strange form of magic, a seeming mix of her old basic spells from the Wizard's academy and her physical tension before an attack. She would have to devote some time in the tower to cultivating this, all things might one day be useful. <br>
<br>
She took a sip of the Neriak Nectar a slave brought her, and silently wished it were Kalish. But that barbarian swill would never be seen inside of this house, and even as Matron of House F'Lok, she could not break against the mores and traditions. ESPECIALLY as Matron... <br>
<br>
A soft sigh escaped her lips, and she realized that if she did not release some of this tension she would become useless to her House AND to the Obsidian Blade. Morrigu smiled widely. Yes, just the excuse she needed... She would go and hunt awhile, to relieve the stress she felt here. She called for a slave and penned a quicknot to her brothers, sealing it with the house crest on her ring. <br>
Off to the hunt... <br>
<br>
Morrigu the Redhand <br>
Family F'Lok <br>
Hand of the Matron of the Obsidian Blade <br>
