<br>
She had been at the Arena with Dantrazz, Trucid, Oifur, Kiros and others of the Blade. Gaelwyn had been asking Trucid to come with him to study with some ridiculous lightdwelling druid. How utterly absurd! When Trucid had been hesitant in her denouncing of his plan, Kiros stepped in appropriately heavy-handed. Morrigu had hovered just behind Gaelwyn, ready to cripple him with her slim stiletto. Eventually, words had turned to actions and she and her comrades found themselves facing a cadre of lightcrawlers, to include Lanneth and Erelas. Dnasiha was there, rabble rousing and striding the fence between the purity of her race and the decadence of the pinkies, as usual. Morrigu had been knocked unconcious by a bolt from the hands of Erelas. <br>
<br>
When she returned to her senses, she saw Natashia there. Laughing to herself, she knew the time was right for this issue to be settled. No woman would have designs on Dantrazz. Morrigu herself often struggled to control her own desires to order his life in acordance with hers, but she had learned that he was much more of a treasure when left free. And here was this woman, who dared to claim that Dantrazz W'Rath would be hers. Eyeing the Necromancer, Morrigu quickly went through her equipment and discarded the idea of using poisons on her. Morrigu knew that if she killed Natashia, it would only foster doubt in the eyes of the man she loved. She would have to trust that Natashia's plans were as her spies had told her. If she could not trust the information coming from her family's network, then she would be dead soon one way or another. <br>
<br>
She hissed a threat at Natashia, and the two began to duel with little breath wasted on any more words. Morrigu opened with a flury of blows, disrupting nearly every spell Natashia was weaving against her. Natashia rallied, leaching the life from Morrigu and stunning her long enough to call upon her shadow-stepping abilities. From that point on, Morrigu had a very hard time catching Natashia to land more than a few glancing blows. I was over in a matter of four our five spells, with Morrigu writhing on the floor of the Arena in agony such as she had not felt since her sparring sessions with her friend Mystere. As she felt the awareness slipping from her, she pulled off one of her silk gloves. dropping it to the floor of the Arena, she brushed sand over it and released herself to the soothing embrace of unconciousness. <br>
<br>
When she awakened, she found herself trapped in this tiny prison cell. Unable to move more than a few inces in any direction, she had calmed her spirit and begun her vigil. And for three days she had tensed and relaxed her muscles in a rythmic motion, gently willing her body to stay in form for the moment one of her captors dared to release her (even if only to kill her). She had been stripped of her weapons and armor, but was not without resources. Her entire body was a lethal tool, honed to perfection in the art of killing. <br>
<br>
A sound approaching broke her from her reverie. The first she had heard in all this time, a single man's footsteps were approaching through a twisted series of hallways. Morrigu breathed a long, shallow breath and relaxed her body, appearing as if she had passed out from dehydration and hunger. The sound of a key fitting into a series of locks, five in all. They were truly afraid of her. &quot;Good&quot;, Morrigu thought to herself. &quot;They should be.&quot; The sound of chains sliding across stone, and a crack of light appeared. Morrigu held her body completely still. The crack widened into a blinding shower of brilliant light, and Morrigu moved like a snake. Blind as a cave bat, she grabbed her jailer's weapon hand and locked onto his wrist, bringing her other hand to his throat to prevent a cry that might rouse the other guards. As the surprised Teir'Dal realized what was happenning his reflexes struck out at her, but he was already dead. Morrigu had crushed his windpipe with her right hand and brought his weapon hand in toward herself, using his own thrust at her abdomen. She brought the arm across the edge of the sarcophagus, cleanly breaking the bones. As the dead man's grip relaxed, Morrigu plucked the dagger from his grasp and stepped into the light. She listened for the sound of more footsteps. but heard none. <br>
<br>
Morrigu took a moment to gather her belongings and take a small sip of water. She let her eyes adjust to the light of the lantern-lit hallway before her, and then padded silently out. The place was one she recognised. The Third Gate of Neriak, deeper than she usually chose to go into the Old Quarter. Morrigu encountered four more guards making her way out into the city. They didn't slow her down much, and they made no sound as they died. <br>
<br>
Morrigu knew that Natashia's plan had been to merely get her out of the way long enough to strike up a consoling affair with Dantrazz. But Natashia had made a horrible mistake... Morrigu knew that this heinous act would reach the ears of her lover, and knew also that Dantrazz would never again look at Natashia with anythiing but hatred and rage. Natashia had stepped into a landmine in Dantrazz' mind laid years ago, with the disappearance of his previous lovers.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/utheredhand.showPublicProfile>TheRedhand</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/image/globalBlack.gif BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Global user</span><br>   <font color=#939393>(3/24/00 12:24:02 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Paying the Piper, Pt. I</span><hr size=1> Pt I <br>
As soon as Morrigu set foot inside the lizard temple of Cazic Thule, word reached her that suring her absence a nameless wood elf had abducted Dantrazz. The bouncers outside of Oggok shivered as they heard a cold and blood-curdling scream pierce the air. Flying into a rage, Morrigu focused her will and was surrounded by a blood-red aura. She ran directly to the wizards pyramid at the heart of the temple's labyrinth, attracting the attention of a horde of lizards on her way there. As the blows rained down upon her, she concentrated on the person she had sworn fealty to and sent her thought with a desperationthat had nothing to do with the attack of the lizards hissing swarming around her. &quot;QUELUI!!!! My Matron, I need thee!&quot; <br>
Deep in the Third Gate of Neriak, Quelui S'Renn sat and studied a newly-aquired text in her quarters. As Morrigu's thoughts came to her she shot up, papers flying everywhere. She immediately knew the location from whence her Hand was crying out to her. With a small gesture of her hands she departed for Cazic Thule. Upon her arrival at the portal, she blinked twice to clear her eyes and gaped at the sight she saw. Very nearly a mountain of lizard corpses were accumulating, and Morrigu was fighting a pitched battle to keep the portal clear of live creatures so that Quelui would have a safe arrival. Out of the corner of her eye, Morrigu saw Quelui's arrival and exhaled a short breath of relief as she gutted another of the seemingly endless lizards. &quot;To the Faydark, quickly!&quot; she cried, and moved in close to Quelui. Not questioning the gravity of the situation, Quelui immendiately began weaving her magicks, and the two dissaappeared in a flurry of light. <br>
Arriving in the greater Faydark forest Morrigu immediately kneeled down (ostensibly to pay homage to her Matron, but mostly because of her utter exhaustion), gasped a deep breath of air and thanked her Matron. She then proceeded to fill Quelui in on the sketchy information she had recieved so far. &quot;And now, Matron, I must get to work. I think that you will not want to be here when I begin...&quot; Noting the cold, dead eyes in Morrigu's face, Quelui nodded briefly and gave her friend as much magickal assistance as she could before stepping back into the portal to go home. <br>
Once alone, Morrigu's jaw set and she began her work...  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#242422><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/utheredhand.showPublicProfile>TheRedhand</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/image/globalBlack.gif BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Global user</span><br>   <font color=#939393>(3/24/00 12:25:06 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Paying the Piper, Pt. II</span><hr size=1> Pt II <br>
Running through the Faydark forest, Morrigu alternated between shouting threats and offering cajolements. She was trying to locate the Wood elf she had heard was involved with her Beloved's abduction. A curious young Feir'Dal approached her. &quot;Why do you make such noise, Dark one? or forest is peaceful and serene. To what end do you cause such a disturbance?&quot; Morrigu wasted no breath on insults and immediately began to terrorize and interrogate the wood elf. Unsatisfied with the information she was recieving, the killing soon began... <br>
<br>
Some few hours and nearly two dozen Feir'Dal bodies later, Morrigu had a name. A name with no family, and few friends it seemed. Kerrina was the bard who had departed to Antonica with designs on Dantrazz W'Rath. Another choice bit of information had been garnered her family's network of spies: Kerrina had been hunting with Lokus and Sensi. Ahh... thought Morrigu, that is so very perfect. In one swoop she could eliminate the hated &quot;spurned&quot; Lokus, his bride, and a foolish young bard who thought that she could claim Dantrazz as a prize. Morrigu made her way to the docks, and boarded the boat for Freeport. She was now calm and confident in the knowledge that she could handle this situation. <br>
<br>
Upon her arrival in Freeport, Morrigu skirted the areas of the town where her quiet and sneaking form might draw unwanted attention. Even she and her band of assassins and spies had places they could not tread, places that meant sure death. And while Morrigu was sure that she would die to save Dantrazz, she was equally sure she would and could not die while his life may still hang in the balance. As she left Freeport behind her, a young apprentice from the Punox family approached her. They secluded themselves in the shade of a nearby tree, and kept watch over each others' shoulders as they conversed in the cant of thieves. &quot;Redhand, a new item for you&quot;. &quot;What is it?&quot; Morrigu hissed impatiently. &quot;We have located the Bard Sensi and the apostate Himself, and it is apparent that neither had anything at all to do with the abduction of Lord W'Rath&quot;. &quot;Are we sure of this?&quot; Morrigu was perplexed. It had all fit together so nicely in her mind. She had been planning her strategy the entire trip over the sea. &quot;Damn...&quot; she whispered &quot;And what of this Kerrina?&quot;. &quot;Of her, Redhand, we have found no trace at all. There is not the slightest sign of either her or Lord W'Rath. Not a bent blade of grass, nor a whisper of a scent. Nothing....we are stymied.&quot; The young Punox visibly tensed as he delivered his report, ready for Morrigu's famous temper to display itself at his expense. But Morrigu was not full of rage. She was fighting her lungs to draw a breath. Her stomach was tying itself in knots, and no amount of control she tried to exercise could stop her panic. &quot;Th..thank you, young one...you are dismissed. Please keep me apprised&quot;. &quot;Mistress, would you li..&quot; &quot;I said GO!!!&quot; Morrigu roared, and the boy scuttled away with preternatural speed, to disappear into the Nektulos forest. Gathering her strength and her nerves, Morrigu began to make her best possible speed to a place she rarely went, and to the person she knew she would find there. Morrigu went to find Sensi.... <br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/utheredhand.showPublicProfile>TheRedhand</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/image/globalBlack.gif BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Global user</span><br>   <font color=#939393>(3/24/00 12:25:49 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Paying the Piper, Pt. III</span><hr size=1> Pt III <br>
<br>
In the Northern plains of Karana, Sensi stood shocked at the sight before her. Here was the woman who had sworn to kill her husband at any time and place of his choosing, with the temerity to approach her as a supplicant seeking assistance. <br>
<br>
&quot;Good day to you, Lady Morrigu, and what is it that you seek?&quot; Sensi asked sweetly, her mind feverishly turning and seeking to make sense of this situation. <br>
<br>
Morrigu maintained rigid composure in front of the Feir'Dal. Her nostrils screamed to flair at the acrid stench of the woman's flesh and sweat, but she remained placid and cool on the exterior. Sensi, I come to you about a mutual loved one, and I seek your assistance to assure his safety...&quot; Morrigu then proceeded to give Sensi all the information she had available, including the link she had learned of between Kerrina and Sensi. <br>
<br>
&quot;This Kerrina is not truly a friend of ours, you have to understand, Morrigu&quot; Sensi said delicately. <br>
<br>
&quot;Then what exactly is she to you, and do you hold any sway at all over her?&quot; Morrigu asked, eager for this whole painful affair to be over and have Sensi set in her task. <br>
<br>
&quot;Well,&quot; Sensi replied, &quot;she is more of a...fan. She rather idolizes Lokus and I: Sensi looked embarassed at the admission. &quot;What is it exactly you wish for me to do?&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot; I do not care what you do, or what means you use to do it. I want Dantrazz back, and I want...&quot; Morrigu's cold facade began to crack. Her voice trembled, and she fought to keep the world around her from spinning crazily. &quot; I WANT for you to find this woman and force her or convince her to release Dantrazz unharmed&quot; Morrigu stated with strength returning to her voice. She eyed Sensi with her well-practiced usual method of intimidating others. <br>
<br>
Sensi looked unfazed by the glare. She did, however, seem concerned about the situation. &quot;Oh, dear&quot; she sighed. &quot;Poor Kerrina...Iwonder what she thinks she is doing.&quot; Sensi shook her head slightly. &quot;So, Morrigu, you wish tyo have your possession returned to you? You are offended that someone else overwrote your designs for Dantrazz, and caged him before you could?&quot; Sensi raised an eyebrow at Morrigu. Sensi was getting to be a better judge of Teir'Dal body language because of her time with Lokus. If her assessment was right, Morrigu's purple complexion and distended throat and forehead veins meant she was only a few moments away from apoplexy. <br>
<br>
&quot;Cage him? I?!? Cage Dantrazz W'Rath?&quot; Morrigu shouted. &quot;I would sooner kill him! Dan is who he is because he has his freedom! Few Teir'Dal earn that! Dan is...&quot; Morrigu trailed off. Her strength departed her, and she crumbled before the wife of her enemy. &quot;Dan is...my light....he is my...salvation....&quot; Sobs wracked her tiny frame, and for the first time, Sensi saw her not as an assassin with the blood of hundreds on her hands, but as a woman. A woman whose life hung in the balance. &quot;Please, Sensi...please, help me to find him. I am so lost without him. Please...&quot; Morrigu's voice dwindled into a tiny whisper. &quot; I will do anything for him. Anything...&quot; <br>
<br>
The words struck Sensi's mind like the ringing of a gong. &quot;Please&quot;, &quot;Help me&quot; and &quot;Anything&quot; were not words she had ever expected to hear from the woman she knew as Morrigu the Redhand. Her heart went out to Morrigu. And yet, at the same time, a thought occured to her. &quot;Anything, eh? And what if the price I name for my help is too costly for you?&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;There is no price too costly for this, Sensi...whatever you ask of me, it shall be done.&quot; Morrigu regained control of herself, sensing that Sensi was willing to help her, but hesitant at what the cost might be. Her wealth? Her status in Teir'Dal society? Her House? Her place in the Blade? All these possibilities passed before Morrigu, and each one was met with approval. Whatever Sensi asked, she would do it. There was no question in her mind. <br>
<br>
&quot;Morrigu, I have never asked you the reason for your vendetta against my husband...&quot; Sensi began. &quot;I wonder, could we talk of it one day?&quot; <br>
<br>
Morrigu tensed at the mention of Lokus the reviled, the spurned. He who had turned away from nearly everything Teir'Dal. Everything except power. He was Teir'Dal to the core, but didn't even admit it to himself. He loved power, revelled in it, and yet he had cast filth upon all that his power had been based upon. <br>
<br>
&quot;And so I tell you now, my price is...&quot; Morrigu's eyes widened in horror as realisation dawned upon her of what Sensi's price would be. &quot;My price is that you leave my husband alone. You and all your servants and 'associates' will never harm him. Do you agree?&quot; <br>
<br>
Morrigu was trapped, and she knew it. There would be no bargaining about this matter. She could strike Sensi down and flee, she could refuse and proudly walk away, she could even locate Lokus and do what she pleased with him. But none of that would be of any help to Dantrazz. <br>
<br>
&quot;My Lady, it will be as you ask of me. Neither I nor any of my House will bring harm upon Lokus...&quot; Morrigu said. &quot;UNTIL such time as you release me from this geas.&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;Come then, Sensi said, preparing a travelling song to speed their way, Let us return to the most likely place. Your information is that she may deal with Shady to get Dan off Antonica? To the Commonlands, then!&quot; <br>
<br>
And with the gentle melody on the air, they sped off on their journey, together.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#242422><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/utheredhand.showPublicProfile>TheRedhand</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/image/globalBlack.gif BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Global user</span><br>   <font color=#939393>(3/24/00 12:37:02 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Paying the Piper, Pt. III - Sensi's tale</span><hr size=1> Sensi bit her lip, confused at what she saw before her. Here was Morrigu... an assassin, a person who she had known to cause nothing but pain to others... here she was, tears streaming down her face, torn apart because of her love for a dear friend of Sensi's. <br>
<br>
She shook her head, and tried to maintain a cool exterior, but inside, she was reeling for what she saw before her. Here was one of her husband's greatest enemies... and she seemed nothing more than a simple woman, a woman like her, whose life had been torn apart because of a simple, young Fier'dal bard's intentions towards her man. <br>
<br>
She barely noticed as she and Morrigu arrived at Shady's. She asked Morrigu to leave before Kerrina showed up... she had her oath. Upon Morrigu's love, upon her honour and her house, she would not harm her husband. This was more than enough for Sensi to feel incredibly different about the woman before her. <br>
<br>
She knew what Morrigu wanted of her... to force Kerrina to tell her what had happened to Dantrazz. But Sensi knew that force would be completely out of the question here... she was dealing with a child. A child of fourteen, who could barely understand the consequences of her actions. A child who had deserved a better life... and Sensi felt deeply responsible for that. <br>
<br>
Humming a quiet tune to herself, her vision brightened and the features of the room stood out in sharp relief. Smiling, she wondered if the Tier'dal really realized what an incredibly gift for vision they had. She watched Morrigu leave the room, and then nodded to herself as she saw her shadow return, sneaking up close to the fire beside Sensi and the standoffish merchant. So her trust extended only so far... Sensi could understand that. <br>
<br>
Presently, she saw Kerrina make her way to the merchant, obviously nervous. Sensi stepped out of the shadows, grateful to have this small gift left behind after her years darting around the shadows of the Faydark. <br>
<br>
&quot;Hello, dear. I've heard you haven't been a very good girl lately.&quot; Sensi spoke gently, comfortingly. <br>
<br>
Kerrina started at the sudden intrusion to her work, obviously surprised to find Sensi there. She stuck out her lower lip and whispered, &quot;I haven't been a very good girl,&quot; tears brimming in her eyes. <br>
<br>
Sensi smiled gently and took Kerrina's hand. &quot;Tell me all about it, dear. I'd like to see this set right.&quot; Mindful of Morrigu's presence so close, she switched to the Elven tongue and kept her conversation very muted. <br>
<br>
&quot;You... you remember Elkrar, do you not?&quot; Kerrina asked Sensi. Sensi nodded silently, a cast of sadness coming about her features. <br>
<br>
&quot;Well... she's very sick, Sensi. The same thing that took her parents... she may not have much time left.&quot; <br>
<br>
Sensi winced at the news, remembering the good times she had had with one of the few Fier'dal she was happy to call friend. &quot;I'm incredibly sorry to hear that, dear, but.. what does that have to do with Dantrazz and Morrigu?&quot; <br>
<br>
Kerrina chewed her lower lip, looking all of her tender age at that moment. &quot;I thought... with Dantrazz and Elkrar's past... she would have liked to see him. But I didn't think Morrigu would ever accept that... would ever let that happen.&quot; <br>
<br>
Sensi blinked back tears, moved by the little bard's intentions, if not her methods. &quot;Yes, dear, I'm sure she would love to see him... but don't you think you should have let Morrigu and Dantrazz work that out for themselves? I'm sure that if it was something he desired, she wouldn't stand in his way.&quot; <br>
<br>
Kerrina nodded sullenly. &quot;I... I didn't think it out so well, I guess. I thought I was doing the right thing.&quot; <br>
<br>
Sensi smiled at the young Fier'dal, seeming the mature elder outwardly, but wishing to scream inwardly. She could see herself... shaking her head, she moved on to the topic at hand. &quot;What did you do with Dantrazz, dear?&quot; Her smile was kind, yet firm. <br>
<br>
Kerrina pouted harder. &quot;I... I put something in his honey mead. He's... he's over in those crates over in the corner.&quot; Giggling a little, she said, &quot;I thought it would be difficult to put an alert and very strong Tier'dal in one.&quot; <br>
<br>
Nodding, Sensi whispered, &quot;I'll make this right, sweetie. I'll try to protect you from Morrigu.. but she's incredibly upset, and I don't think without reason. Best you leave before she shows up.&quot; <br>
<br>
A brief flash of fear went through Kerrina's eyes, and she began to speed off... just a muttered, &quot;Tell her I'm sorry,&quot; left behind in the humid air. <br>
<br>
Turning to address Morrigu directly, Sensi smiled at the Tier'dal rogue, who was obviously startled at Sensi's knowledge of her presence. <br>
<br>
&quot;You'll find your love in those crates in the corner. I'm sorry this happened.. and I can't say I don't empathize with Kerrina's motives, if not her actions. Dantrazz's first fiancee... a Fier'dal druid, and a dear friend of mine.. lies dying in Kelethin. Kerrina took it upon herself to bring Elkrar a brief moment of happiness in her last days. She is sorry she handled this so inappropriately. I just think she should have consulted the two of you about it instead of pouring a potion into his mead. I will trust that you will tell him of this, and he and you can deal with it directly. And I trust that you will honour our agreement.&quot; <br>
<br>
Sensi unslung her drum from her shoulder and began to speed off down the tunnel towards the Commonlands. She smiled slightly to herself as she heard Morrigu's exclimation of happiness and Dantrazz's muted, drugged questions before her speed carried her out of earshot and into the sunshine that was just cresting above the mountains.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <br><font color=#939393>- </font><a href=http://pub10.ezboard.com/bshadowsoftheblade>House W'Rath</a><font color=#939393> - </font><a href=http://pub10.ezboard.com/fshadowsofthebladecharacterstoriesbackgroundsandsuch>Character Stories (Backgrounds and Such)</a> <font color=#939393> - </font><a href="http://members.home.net/sbugelli">House W'Rath Common Hall</a><font color=#939393> - </font><br><br><br><br>Powered By <a href=http://www.ezboard.com/>ezboard®</a> Ver. 6.4 b8<br>Copyright ©1999-2001 ezboard, Inc.</center></body></html>  